@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xviii) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses an INDEX ASSIGNMENT (`xs[1] = 99` — an `SAssign` statement
-- with a non-bare-name lvalue). eval mutates the element in place (the list is held by a
-- `mut` binding); the compute spine lowers only a bare-name reassignment (D1(xiv)) — the
-- `block` SBind path requires the target to be a plain in-scope name, and a field/index
-- lvalue is a distinct `SAssign` AST node it does not yet lower, so it refuses. The
-- differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler
-- frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals; D1(xvi) PAST duration literals; D1(xvii) PAST `for`
-- comprehensions; D1(xviii) PAST integer RANGES (`1..n`/`1..=n` → a list; see
-- compile_range_test). The frontier now sits at FIELD/INDEX ASSIGNMENT. This file uses one,
-- so it still refuses; when an `SAssign` to an lvalue lowers (a later D1 slice, an in-place
-- element/field write), it flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def main(): Unit
  let mut xs = [10, 20, 30]
  xs[1] = 99
  print(xs)
